    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-12-04T11:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-12-04T11:00:00-05:00" n="970"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d970">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00116 EW/12–444: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Ireland</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gray</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Dublin</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-12-04T17:00:00+01:00"
                            >December 4, 1944—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 5:48 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>214. Reurtel 231, December l.<note n="79" xml:id="d970fn79">See footnote 78, <hi
                            rend="italic">supra.</hi>
                    </note> Appreciate your cable. Now that the record has been established, whether
                    war criminals come here or not, we think your line of handling the matter the
                    best that could be taken. Releasing Irish <hi rend="italic">aide-mémoire</hi>
                    reply to American press without further comment than expressing the wish that
                    the assurances had gone farther was most effective here. More than anything
                    External <pb facs="1466" n="1452" xml:id="pg_1452"/> Affairs is apprehensive of
                    unfavorable American press. Eventual possible publication of further
                    representations made to continental neutrals will, we think, have more weight
                    here than direct representations to Eire Government which might be susceptible
                    of interpretation as threats and exploited for local political ends. Whatever
                    Brennan may be instructed to tell you, we place no confidence in any verbal
                    assurances as to De Valera’s intentions. We believe that if he felt it to be his
                    immediate political advantage he would make a point of emphasizing his
                    independence by granting asylum and stand pat on his unequivocal reply.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gray</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
